		<td><b>Waveform plotting?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />- Any idea about coding a "waveform visualizer" while the music is playing, much like Winamp or WindowsMediaPlayer styles? You know, the wave is draw while the music plays, or some artistic graphics.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sat Jan 10, 2009 8:11 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Ideas:
<br /><ul><li>Take the log(period) and volume of each channel, and use those coordinates to draw something. </li><li>Make a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goertzel_algorithm" class="postlink">Goertzel</a> spectral analyzer. First pass the audio waveform through a bank of resonant filters spaced a half octave apart (center frequency ratio of sqrt(2):1). For each 1/60 s and each bank, take the sum of the squares of the filter's output, and then take the log of this sum. This gives you the "power spectrum" of the signal, which you can draw as vertical bars, etc. </li><li>Play with Winamp AVS for a while. </li></ul>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
